As an introverted creative working independently and placing great value on privacy, it should not be contradictory, but it often is. Most online sources and coaches advise working with the (evil) tech giants and behaving extrovertedly. Advertise here, follow the algorithm, show your personality. Get a blue checkmark on that service, be available around the clock, respond to inquiries with a video of yourself, answer immediately. Video, video, video.
1/3
For me, this is a year of changes.
I do not want to feed the tech giants with money, data, and my energy. Or coaches who have their own extroverted solution and try to sell it to everyone. I am looking for new ways to run my business and am simultaneously fighting against my long-held belief that one must do something in a certain way to succeed.
Wish me luck!
I have already taken the first steps.
I cancelled Facebook, removed all Meta and Pinterest trackers from my website, and deleted my private WhatsApp account.
Yesterday, I also removed Google Analytics, the last external tracker from my website, and feel good about it.
Recently, I subscribed to a European CRM to have better DSGVO support, and will move my business there in the coming weeks.
I have transferred my MX account to Proton and now have full SPF, DKIM, and DMARC without having to pay anything to Google for normal email validation.
3/3
